text: Whitey Bulger's Longtime Companion Catherine Greig Pleads Not Guilty to Contempt Charges
label: title

text: Whitey Bulger's Longtime Companion Catherine Greig Pleads Not Guilty to Contempt Charges (ABC News)
label: nolabel

text: The longtime companion of convicted Boston mob boss James "
label: body

text: pleaded not guilty today to federal contempt charges for refusing to tell a grand jury who helped them go on the lam.
label: body

text: was seen in her native South Boston neighborhood since the couple fled in 1995 and became fugitives.
label: body

text: Wearing blue prison scrubs, her white hair cut close, Catherine Greig, 64, waved enthusiastically to her sister Margaret as she was led into federal court on criminal contempt charges for refusing to cooperate with a grand jury "investigation into third parties who assisted and harbored" Bulger while the couple hid for 16 years until their arrest in 2011 at a Santa Monica, California, hideout, where authorities said they were using the pseudonyms Charlie and Carol Gasko.
label: body

text: Bulger, 86, was found guilty in 2013 in connection with 11 murders, drug dealing, extortion and other charges connected to the violence he unleashed on Boston for decades while also secretly working as a longtime top echelon informant for the
label: body

text: field office in Boston. He is serving two life sentences.
label: body

text: Catherine Greig, 'Whitey' Bulger's Girlfriend, Pleads Guilty
label: nolabel

text: Whitey Bulger Writes Contrite Letter to Teens, Says His Life Was 'Spent Foolishly'
label: nolabel

text: Greig's attorney, Kevin Reddington, called the latest charges against Greig "a form of harrassment" and pointed out that Greig could be forced to serve more time than some of the killers who worked under Bulger in the Winter Hill Gang. Hitman John Martorano, who confessed to killing 20 people, served 12 years in federal prison as part of a federal plea agreement and is now a fixture at some high-end Boston eateries.
label: body

text: "She's in good spirits," Reddington said of his client. "She is looking forward to the trial. She has done nothing wrong."
label: body

text: Steve Davis, whose sister, Debbie Davis, was among the victims Bulger was charged with murdering in 1981, said seeing Greig in court made him "sick to my stomach." Bulger was not convicted of killing Davis but her body was recovered in a shallow grave near the Neponset River in what has been dubbed the "Bulger graveyard."
label: body

text: Federal prosecutors said Greig refused to cooperate with a grand jury investigation probing anyone who may have helped her and Bulger hide as fugitives for 16 years. Reddington said she has "nothing to offer" investigators.
label: body

text: Greig pleaded guilty in 2012 to federal charges of harboring a fugitive and identity theft and was sentenced to 8 years, a sentence she is serving at a minimum-security prison in Minnesota. Last month, federal prosecutors in Boston charged her with criminal contempt for what the FBI said is hindering an investigation into who helped the couple hide.
label: body

text: "Catherine Greig has yet again failed to do the right thing," FBI Special Agent Joseph Bonavolonta said in a statement after the charges were announced. "Her refusal to testify has hindered the FBI's efforts to seek justice for the victims of his crimes. Our efforts to find those who assisted them during their lives as fugitives will not stop despite the fact that Ms. Greig has refused to testify."
label: body

text: Reddington told ABC News earlier that the government is targeting Greig "in a vindictive and harassing way." He pointed out that the prosecutor who is investigating his client was among the attendees at a red carpet premiere of "Black Mass," a movie based on the book by the same name by former Boston Globe reporters Dick Lehr and Gerry O'Neill chronicling Bulger's rise from street thug to mob boss with the help of crooked FBI handlers.
label: body

text: "Prosecutors are going to the movies while they are trying to send my client to jail for a longer period of time," Reddington said.
label: body

text: Assistant United States Attorney Fred Wyshak attended last month's red carpet cast premiere of "Black Mass." Wyshak told ABC News at the event that he enjoyed the movie. Bulger worked as a paid FBI informant starting in 1975, along with his top lieutenant, Stephen "The Rifleman" Flemmi.
label: body

text: Wyshak's character in "Black Mass" was played by actor Corey Stoll. Wyshak attended the premiere with his wife and former federal prosecutor Brian Kelly.
label: body

text: Poll: Trump Hits Highest Mark Yet, But Carson Is Close Behind
label: title

text: War of Words Breaks Out Between Trump and Bush Over 9/11
label: nolabel

text: Real estate mogul Donald Trump remains the front-runner in the Republican presidential field, while former neurosurgeon Ben Carson holds a close second place, a new NBC News/Wall Street Journal poll shows.
label: body

text: With the backing of 25 percent of Republican primary voters, Trump is at his highest level of support in the poll since entering the 2016 race. Carson now gets the support of 22 percent of Republican voters, remaining within the margin of error of his first-place rival. Last month, 21 percent of GOP primary voters said Trump was their first choice for the party's nomination, while 20 percent picked Carson.
label: body

text: Sen. Marco Rubio of Florida is in third place, getting support from 13 percent of GOP voters, while Sen. Ted Cruz of Texas (at 9 percent, up four points since last month ) and Jeb Bush (at 8 percent, up one point since last month) are in fourth and fifth place, respectively.
label: body

text: The new poll, which surveyed respondents from Oct. 15 to Sunday, saw a slight dip in support for former Hewlett-Packard executive Carly Fiorina, who fell from 11 percent last month to 7 percent this month. Fiorina won a boost late this summer from strong performances in the two televised Republican debates.
label: body

text: Receiving support in the low single digits in the poll are former Arkansas Gov. Mike Huckabee (3 percent), Ohio Gov. John Kasich (3 percent), Sen. Rand Paul of Kentucky (2 percent) and New Jersey Gov. Chris Christie (1 percent).
label: body

text: Five candidates still in the race ‚Äî Sen. Lindsey Graham of South Carolina, former Sen. Rick Santorum of Pennsylvania, former New York Gov. George Pataki, Louisiana Gov. Bobby Jindal and former Virginia Gov. Jim Gilmore ‚Äî registered less than 1 percent support.
label: body

text: While Trump leads when GOP primary voters are asked about their first choice for the party's nomination, Carson boasts the highest share of voters who say they can see themselves supporting him. Seventy-four percent said that they can imagine backing Carson for the GOP nod, while just 20 percent said they could not.
label: body

text: But Trump has also gained ground when it comes to whether or not potential voters can picture themselves backing him. Fifty-nine percent of GOP voters now say they can see themselves supporting Trump, while 36 percent disagree. Just last month, a slight majority ‚Äî 52 percent ‚Äî said they could not see themselves backing the real estate mogul, while 47 could envision it.
label: body

text: Rubio (65 percent could support/26 percent could not support) and Fiorina (56 could support/30 percent could not support) also show significant possible upsides among GOP voters.
label: body

text: The gap is narrower for Bush (51 percent could support/44 percent could not support) and Cruz (48 percent could support/41 percent could not support.)
label: body

text: When asked which candidate would be their second choice, GOP respondents tended to choose Carson, followed by Trump and Rubio. That tally means that, when GOP primary voters' first and second choices are combined, the former neurosurgeon manages to best Trump, 44 percent to 39 percent.
label: body

text: Carson runs strongest among very conservative Republicans, with 28 percent of that group's support, while Trump leads among those who say they are moderate or liberal (31 percent). Trump also leads among GOP primary voters who listen to talk radio (33 percent to Carson's 22 percent) and those who describe themselves as Tea Party supporters (28 percent to Carson's 22 percent).
label: body

text: The NBC News/ Wall Street Journal poll was conducted Oct. 15 to 18. The margin of error for 400 Republican primary voters is +/- 4.9 percent.

text: , Dr. Boyko said, the first time this has been done for such a large and diverse group of dogs, more than 4,500 dogs of 161 breeds and 549 village dogs from 38 countries. That allowed the researchers to determine which geographic groups of modern dogs were closest to ancestral populations genetically. And that led them to Central Asia as the place of origin for dogs in much the same way that genetic studies have located the origin of modern humans in East Africa.
label: body

text: The analysis, Dr. Boyko said, pointed to Central Asia, including Mongolia and Nepal, as the place where ‚Äúall the dogs alive today‚Äù come from. The data did not allow precise dating of the origin, he said, but showed it occurred at least 15,000 years ago. They reported their findings Monday in
label: body

text: Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences
label: body

text: Greger Larson of Oxford University, who is leading an international effort to analyze ancient DNA from fossilized bones, said he was impressed by the scope of the study. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs really great to see not just the sheer number of street dogs, but also the geographic breadth and the number of remote locations where the dogs were sampled,‚Äù he said. He also praised the sampling of different kinds of DNA and the analytic methods.
label: body

text: But in the world of dog studies, very little is definitive. The most recent common ancestor of today‚Äôs dogs lived in Central Asia, Dr. Boyko said, although he cannot rule out the possibility that some dogs could have been domesticated elsewhere and died out. Or dogs domesticated elsewhere could have gone to Central Asia from somewhere else and then diversified into all the canines alive today, he said.
label: body

text: Dr. Larson, who was not involved with the study, said he thought the Central Asia finding required further testing. He said he suspected that the origins of modern dogs were ‚Äúextremely messy‚Äù and that no amount of sampling of living populations would be definitive. He said a combination of studies of modern and ancient DNA was necessary.
label: body

text: Dr. Boyko said the research for the first time studied three sources of DNA from purebred and village dogs worldwide. The team analyzed DNA from all the chromosomes in the cell nucleus, from the Y chromosome specifically, found only in males, and from mitochondria, cellular energy machines outside the nucleus that are inherited from the mother.
label: body

text: Dr. Boyko traveled to a number of the locations where blood was drawn from village dogs. He said: ‚ÄúThe great thing about working with dogs is that if you show up with food you don‚Äôt usually have trouble recruiting subjects. Usually.‚Äù
label: body

text: He added: ‚ÄúWe showed up in Puerto Rico at a fishing village and the dogs turned up their noses at roast beef sandwiches. They were used to eating fish entrails.‚Äù

text: Top California official pushes ammo background checks
label: title

text: CA official pitches tighter gun rules
label: nolabel

text: Gun control advocates are launching a new regulatory push in California to impose first-in-the-nation instant background checks for ammunition sales, a move that comes as gun violence surfaces as a lightning rod issue in the 2016 presidential race.¬†
label: body

text: Lt. Gov. Gavin Newsom, a Democratic candidate for governor in 2018, joined with the Law Center to Prevent Gun Violence in announcing the initiative last week.¬†
label: body

text: The November 2016 ballot initiative, which already is being slammed by the National Rifle Association and other gun rights groups, would make changes on several fronts.¬†
label: body

text: It would require owners to turn in "large-capacity" magazines -- those holding 11 rounds or more -- and report when their weapons are stolen. Perhaps the most controversial provision would handle ammo sales like gun sales by requiring "point-of-sale background checks" for ammunition purchases; dealers also would need a license similar to those required to sell firearms.¬†
label: body

text: As New York has backed off a similar initiative, California would be the first state to enact such background checks, if the initiative is successful. Four states -- Connecticut, Illinois, Massachusetts and New Jersey -- require ammunition purchasers to obtain permits ahead of time, according to the initiative's supporters.¬†
label: body

text: The proposal comes in the wake of high-profile killings nationwide and three in the San Francisco Bay Area that were tied to stolen guns.¬†
label: body

text: "Stuff doesn't just have to happen," Newsom said last week, responding to comments by Republican presidential candidate Jeb Bush about a recent mass shooting on an Oregon college campus. "We have the ability to step in with some common sense. We have the ability to protect our families."¬†
label: body

text: But the National Rifle Association said Newsom's effort would chip away at Second Amendment rights.¬†
label: body

text: The NRA has been tangling with Democratic presidential candidates in recent days after several made gun laws a rallying cry at the lead-off 2016 primary debate.¬†
label: body

text: Asked at the debate which "enemy" he's most proud of, former Maryland Gov. Martin O'Malley said: "The National Rifle Association." Hillary Clinton also included the NRA on her enemies list.¬†
label: body

text: Aside from the ammo background checks, the California proposal also would require felons to relinquish weapons, and ensure that data is shared with the federal firearms database on residents who are prohibited from owning guns.¬†
label: body

text: Gun control advocates welcomed California's proposal, pointing to the lack of political will at the federal level. Newsom made his announcement in San Francisco near the site of a 1993 gun massacre that helped spur federal restrictions on assault weapons.¬†
label: body

text: "Congress has failed to pass even the most basic laws to help keep guns out of dangerous hands and save lives," said Kate Folmar, spokeswoman for Everytown for Gun Safety, a group founded by former New York Mayor Michael Bloomberg. "The states have and will continue to take action to reduce gun violence despite the gridlock in Washington."¬†
label: body

text: Polls have shown California voters are generally more supportive of restricting access to guns than voters in other states.¬†
label: body

text: The Associated Press contributed to this report.

text: They were identical twin boys, Wyatt and Jonas Maines, adopted at birth in 1997 by middle-class, conservative parents. Healthy and happy, they were physically indistinguishable from each other, but even as infants their personalities seemed to diverge.
label: body

text: By the age of 2, when the boys were just learning to speak, Wyatt asked his mother, ‚ÄúWhen do I get to be a girl?‚Äù and ‚ÄúWhen will my penis fall off?‚Äù It was the beginning of a journey through questions of gender that would challenge a mother to find ways to help her child, even as the father pushed back. The father would learn the truest meaning of family only after his wife felt forced to file a lawsuit against the twins‚Äô elementary school, and when Jonas told him, at age 9, ‚ÄúFace it, Dad, you have a son and a daughter.‚Äù
label: body

text: Nicole and Jonas, who grew up primarily in Maine, just turned 18. In ‚ÄúBecoming Nicole: The Transformation of an American Family,‚Äù published this week by Random House and excerpted below, Washington Post science writer Amy Ellis Nutt explores the remarkable story of an ordinary family navigating its way through extraordinary times.
label: body

text: Jonas and Nicole Maines are first-year students at the University of Maine.                                                                            (Bill O'Leary/The Washington Post)

label: nolabel

text: Wyatt ‚Äî who later became Nicole ‚Äî and Jonas Maines as babies. Scientists say that differences in biological sex are not necessarily hard-wired or absolute.                                                                            (Courtesy of Maines Family)

text: With the boys about to begin first grade, the family decided to hold a ‚ÄúGet to Know the Maineses‚Äù party for the neighborhood. It was a cool, cloudy day as guests streamed into the house. Kelly was still in the kitchen fixing platters of food, but with the party starting, Wayne went looking for the boys. He found Jonas in the den, then Wyatt appeared at the top of the stairs, smiling down excitedly at his father. There he was, his parents‚Äô sweet, irrepressible, chestnut-haired boy ‚Äî wearing his favorite pink princess dress from Toys R Us.
label: body

text: Wyatt Maines' self-portrait, at age seven.                                                                            (Courtesy of Maines Family)
font-family: FranklinITCProLight, 'Franklin Gothic', 'ITC Franklin Gothic', Arial, sans-serif
label: nolabel

text: Wayne‚Äôs harsh tone cracked through the party chatter, and Wyatt‚Äôs little body jerked, then froze. Kelly, who heard her husband‚Äôs strained voice from the kitchen, knew something was wrong and rushed out.
label: body

text: Kelly followed her husband‚Äôs eyes to the top of the stairs. One of Wyatt‚Äôs tiny hands grasped the banister; the other clutched a glittery wand. On his face was fear and confusion.
label: body

text: ‚ÄúAre you going to let him wear that?‚Äù Wayne asked.
label: body

text: Kelly didn‚Äôt answer. Instead, she raced up to Wyatt, hot tears now streaking his face, took him by the hand and led him back into his bedroom. It was, she knew right then and there, the worst moment of her life. It wasn‚Äôt so much the reaction of the people at the party, who were mostly stunned into silence ‚Äî that was Wayne‚Äôs issue ‚Äî but rather the hurt her son was experiencing, and for no good reason other than that he wanted to wear his princess dress to the family‚Äôs party. How could she explain to him that he‚Äôd done nothing wrong when his father had just scolded him? She didn‚Äôt think she was ready for this, and yet she knew it was just the beginning.
label: body

text: ‚ÄúThis isn‚Äôt really the right time,‚Äù Kelly gently told Wyatt, persuading him it would be better, for now, to wear pants and a shirt.
label: body

font-family: FranklinITCProLight, 'Franklin Gothic', 'ITC Franklin Gothic', Arial, sans-serif
label: nolabel

text: ‚ÄúI can‚Äôt be myself,‚Äù Wyatt said, a mixture of sadness and anger in his voice. ‚ÄúJonas gets to wear what he wants. Why can‚Äôt I?‚Äù
label: body

text: Kelly knew it was true, and that it wasn‚Äôt fair.
label: body

text: ‚ÄúLet‚Äôs just try to get to know people first,‚Äù she said.
label: body

text: The Maineses in front of the Supreme Court during a family trip to Washington.                                                                            (Courtesy of Maines Family)
font-family: FranklinITCProLight, 'Franklin Gothic', 'ITC Franklin Gothic', Arial, sans-serif
label: nolabel

text: Still dazed, Wayne remained downstairs, enveloped in a kind of concussive quiet. The world where he was a father and husband in an ordinary, hard-working, middle-class family had just blown up. He stood there stunned, unable to hear whatever was going on around him, as if deafened by the psychological explosion. Was everyone at the party looking at him right now? He felt strangely alone, and, worse, unmasked. As if the hunter, the fisherman, the Air Force veteran and the Republican had all been stripped away and the only thing left was the father ‚Äî but father of what and of whom? Yes, he was a happily married man and the parent of two beautiful boys, but it was also true he was embarrassed by one of them ‚Äî and he‚Äôd just broken that little boy‚Äôs heart.
label: body

text: From a young age, Wyatt was moodier than Jonas; he would occasionally lash out at his brother as if frustrated just by his presence. There was something else, too. At night, when the boys were very little and she bathed them, Kelly would catch Wyatt staring into the long mirror hanging on the inside of the bathroom door. As she pulled off Jonas‚Äôs clothes and plunked him into the tub, she‚Äôd notice Wyatt standing naked and transfixed in front of the mirror. What did the 2-year-old see? Himself? His identical twin brother?
label: body

text: It was impossible to know, and impossible to ask Wyatt, of course. But often it seemed as if the little boy was puzzled by his reflection, unsure of the image staring back. There was some inscrutable pain behind his eyes. He seemed tense and anxious, as if his heart was in knots and he didn‚Äôt know how to untie them.

text: How can one identical twin be transgender and the other not?
label: nolabel

text: (Gillian Brockell, Jorge Ribas and Monica Akhtar)
font-family: FranklinITCProLight, 'Franklin Gothic', 'ITC Franklin Gothic', Arial, sans-serif
label: nolabel

text: Humans have long thought they could control the sex of a newborn, or, at the very least, influence whether a baby would be born male or female. Ancient Romans believed if a pregnant woman carried the egg of a chicken close to her breast, she would give birth to a boy. Artistotle contended that conception on the day of a strong north wind would result in a male child, on the day of a strong south wind, a female. Hippocrates‚Äôs solution, perhaps, was the simplest, if also the most painful: binding of the right testicle for the birth of a girl; binding the left for a boy.
label: body

text: There is no shortage of only slightly more sophisticated theories today. But what we know for sure is that we all begin life essentially genderless, at least in terms of sexual anatomy. The last of our 23 pairs of chromosomes makes us either genetic males (XY) or genetic females (XX). But there are at least 50 genes that play a part in sexual identity development and are expressed at different levels early on.
label: body

text: Sexual anatomy, however, is determined in large part by hormones. All of us begin, in utero, with an opening next to the anus and a kind of genital ‚Äúbud.‚Äô‚Äô The addition of testosterone drives the fetus in the male direction. An inhibiting hormone prevents males from developing internal female reproductive organs. Without testosterone, the embryo develops in the female direction.
label: body

text: Sexual differentiation of the genitals happens at about six weeks, but the sexual differentiation of the brain, including gender identity and the setting of our gender behavior, is, at least partly, a distinct process. Again, hormones play the crucial role, with surges of testosterone indirectly ‚Äúmasculinizing‚Äù the brains of some fetuses, causing subtle but distinct differences in brain structure and functional activity.
label: body

text: For instance, the straight gyrus, a narrow strip that runs along the midline on the undersurface of the frontal lobe, is about 10 percent larger in women than men. The straight gyrus, scientists have found, is highly correlated with social cognition ‚Äî that is, interpersonal awareness.
label: body

text: These same scientists, however, caution that differences in biological sex are not necessarily hard-wired or absolute. In adults, they found that regardless of biological sex, the larger the straight gyrus, the more ‚Äúfeminine‚Äù the behavior. For most males, the action of male hormones on the brain is crucial to the development of male gender identity. A mutation of an androgen receptor on the X chromosome can cause androgen insensitivity syndrome, in which virilization of the brain fails, and when it does, a baby will be born chromosomally male (XY) and have testes rather than ovaries but also a short vagina, and the child‚Äôs outward appearance will be female. Its gender identity is nearly always female.
label: body

text: In other words, our genitals and our gender identity are not the same. Sexual anatomy and gender identity are the products of two different processes, occurring at distinctly different times and along different neural pathways before we are even born. Both are functions of genes as well as hormones, and while sexual anatomy and gender identity usually match, there are dozens of biological events that can affect the outcome of the latter and cause an incongruence between the two.
label: body

text: In some ways, the brain and the body are two very different aspects of what it means to be human, especially when it comes to sex and gender. Who we are, male or female, is a brain process, but what we look like at birth, what we develop into at puberty, who we are attracted to and how we act ‚Äî male, female or something in between ‚Äî are all embedded in different groups of brain cells with different patterns of growth and activity. Ultimately gender identity is the result of biological processes and is a function of the interplay between sex hormones and the developing brain, and because it is a process that takes place over time, in utero, it can be influenced by any number of environmental effects.
label: body

text: The idea of a name change for Wyatt had been hanging over the family as the boys advanced through elementary school. If they were going to let Wyatt look like a girl and dress like a girl, then surely he deserved a girl‚Äôs name.
label: body

text: When they asked Wyatt what name he‚Äôd like, he said, ‚ÄúRaven,‚Äù a character on one of his favorite television shows.
label: body

text: ‚ÄúThat‚Äôs not a real name,‚Äù Wayne complained. ‚ÄúThat‚Äôs a TV name.‚Äù
label: body

text: But TV names were the ones with which Wyatt was most familiar. He considered Quinn, a character on the Nickelodeon teen comedy/drama ‚ÄúZoey 101,‚Äù but he kept stumbling over the spelling. Finally, he settled on Nicole, or Nikki for short, one of Zoey‚Äôs sidekicks.
label: body

font-family: FranklinITCProLight, 'Franklin Gothic', 'ITC Franklin Gothic', Arial, sans-serif
label: nolabel

text: Whether Nicole or Nikki, it was difficult for Wayne to get the name out, so he tried to avoid using either. Once again, still feeling ambivalent, he left it to Kelly to sort out the details. When she called the family lawyer, she quickly discovered legally changing a name wasn‚Äôt nearly as simple as filling out a form. In Maine, by law, name changes are announced in the newspaper. If the Maineses wanted to keep this out of the public eye, they‚Äôd have to petition the court to make an exception. The last thing Kelly and Wayne wanted was to make some public announcement, no matter how small, that their son was now their daughter.
label: body

text: Wayne and Nicole Maines at an April 2015 gala in Boston honoring Dr. Norman Spack, Nicole‚Äôs doctors, who co-founded the first clinic in the United States to treat transgender children.                                                                            (Courtesy of Maines Family)
font-family: FranklinITCProLight, 'Franklin Gothic', 'ITC Franklin Gothic', Arial, sans-serif
label: nolabel

text: Before any petition would be granted, however, the parents had to appear in person at the county courthouse. Seated in the small courtroom on a hot summer day, Kelly and Wayne fidgeted nervously waiting for the judge. When he finally entered, their hearts sank just a bit ‚Äî he was an elderly gentleman, probably over 70, with white hair, and a pair of sneakers peeking out from under his black robe.
label: body

text: ‚ÄúWhy are you changing your son‚Äôs name to a girl‚Äôs name?‚Äù he asked.
label: body

text: Kelly‚Äôs back arched slightly. Their lawyer, or rather the real estate attorney filling in for their lawyer, answered, ‚ÄúTheir daughter is a transgender child, Your Honor, and has been presenting as a girl for a number of years. The parents, doctors and counselors agree this is the right thing to do at this time.‚Äù
label: body

text: ‚ÄúWhy are you petitioning to keep this out of the paper?‚Äù
label: body

text: ‚ÄúDue to the recent protests .‚Äâ.‚Äâ. by the Christian Civic League, they are requesting this to be kept private,‚Äù the attorney answered, referring to a local, politically active organization with vehemently anti-gay and anti-transgender views.
label: body

font-family: FranklinITCProLight, 'Franklin Gothic', 'ITC Franklin Gothic', Arial, sans-serif
label: nolabel

text: ‚ÄúMaybe the Christian Civic League should appear in court to have their say,‚Äù the judge said.
label: body

text: What the hell is going on? Wayne thought. Kelly‚Äôs eyes welled and Wayne shifted uncomfortably in his seat. Wayne, who‚Äôd had such a hard time making this adjustment, knew he had to do something. He raised his hand and asked if he could say something.
label: body

text: Wayne explained that his son Wyatt had been expressing feelings he was a girl from the age of 2 and that his insistence he was born in the wrong body had made it difficult for him in school. They were convinced, and Wyatt‚Äôs doctors agreed, that he should be allowed to transition to being a girl.
label: body

text: ‚ÄúI see no reason to deny your request,‚Äù the judge said. ‚ÄúYou are obviously very concerned about your child‚Äôs safety.‚Äù
label: body

text: For Wayne, this was the first time he‚Äôd shown any kind of public support for Wyatt being transgender. His instincts as a father had been tested without his even realizing it, and he‚Äôd responded to the challenge.
label: body

text: The petition was granted, and in a matter of days Wyatt Benjamin Maines would officially and legally become Nicole Amber Maines. The middle name was Kelly‚Äôs idea. She just liked the sound of it. Ultimately, the name change and petition were relatively easy. What neither Kelly nor Wayne knew as they walked out of the courtroom was that everyone‚Äôs life was about to get a lot harder.
label: body

text: Egypt is holding its first parliamentary elections since 2011, and no one is showing up to the polls.
label: body

text: Turnout was so low on Sunday the government gave state workers a
label: body

text: to encourage people to go vote.
label: body

text: Prime Minister Sherif Ismail said there was 15 to 16 percent voting turnout on Sunday, but Reuters correspondents
label: body

text: For a country that tipped the Arab Spring by ousting Hosni Mubarak in 2011 and protested again, leading to the ousting of democratically-elected president Mohamed Morsi, in 2013, this would seem like some seriously uncharacteristic political apathy ‚Äî except it‚Äôs anything but.
label: body

text: Young people are refusing to vote out of frustration and lack of faith in the political system.
label: body

text: Since President Abdel Fattah el-Sisi, the former military general who ousted Morsi and was officially elected president in 2014, took power, there has been a crackdown on political dissidents, including the Muslim Brotherhood.
label: body

text: There have¬†been many¬†arrests and harsh sentences, including death, for protesters and journalists. Young people view some interruptions ‚Äî like WhatsApp and Skype calls apparently being
label: body

text: ‚Äî as governmental attempts to cut off their communication and free speech.
label: body

text: There is no major opposition party in this election, and it¬†is expected to bring in only Sisi-supporting politicians. Although there is still significant support for Sisi among Egyptians, the lack of opposition adds¬†to the evidence that political freedom is¬†considerably low¬†in the country.
label: body

text: Young people are the popular force in Egypt, and they are making their stance clear with this election.
label: body

text: Canada election: Harper, Mulcair and Trudeau in tight race
label: title

text: Stephen Harper, Tom Mulcair and Justin Trudeau turned out in their constituencies on Monday morning
label: nolabel

text: Is Canada's new PM the only world leader with a tattoo?
label: nolabel

text: Five things Stephen Harper got wrong
label: nolabel

text: Trudeau brings Liberals back on top
label: nolabel

text: Seven things Justin Trudeau believes in
label: nolabel

text: Canadians have voted in parliamentary elections that could bring the first new leader in nearly 10 years.
label: body

text: Incumbent Conservative PM Stephen Harper is fighting for a rare fourth term but the frontrunner is Liberal leader Justin Trudeau.
label: body

text: Early counts in the eastern provinces show the Liberals ahead in all 32 seat races there.
label: body

text: Mr Trudeau is now poised to form the next government, Canada's CBC and CTV networks predict.
label: body

text: They say it is still unclear whether it will be a majority or minority government.
label: body

text: As the first results from Atlantic Canada began pouring in, former Conservative Justice Minister Peter MacKay said: "A sea of change here. We are used to high tides in Atlantic Canada. This is not what we hoped for."
label: body

text: The Liberal Party was always expected to perform well in the region.
label: body

text: The Conservatives are now in danger of losing all 13 seats they held in Atlantic Canada in 2011.
label: body

text: A third party, the left-leaning New Democratic Party (NDP), could also play a decisive role in whether Mr Harper and his Conservatives lose power.
label: body

text: Voting hours were staggered across the country and polls opened in Newfoundland at 08:30 local time (11:00 GMT). Polls closed in the west of the country at 19:00 (02:00 GMT).
label: body

text: It is one of the longest and possibly closest election campaigns in Canada's history, with leaders criss-crossing the country to try to sway undecided voters.
label: body

text: To form a majority government, a party needs 170 seats in the 338-member parliament.
label: body

text: Mr Harper, 56, is selling himself as the steady hand who can steer Canada's troubled economy back on track.
label: body

text: His campaign has run TV advertisements saying that Liberal leader Mr Trudeau, 43, is "just not ready" to take office.
label: body

text: Queues were reported at some polling stations
label: nolabel

text: Justin Trudeau, seen here at the head of the human pyramid, started the campaign in third place
label: nolabel

text: "Every single vote for a Conservative candidate is a vote to protect our economy against Liberal and NDP deficits and taxes," Mr Harper told supporters in Regina, Saskatchewan, on Sunday.
label: body

text: As polls opened, he tweeted that a vote for the Conservatives would "
label: body

text: protect Canadian jobs and our economy
label: body

text: Mr Trudeau started the race in third place but the Liberals took the lead in opinion polls in a late surge.
label: body

text: At the scene - Rajini Vaidyanathan, BBC News, Toronto
label: body

text: The Toronto Blue Jays have their first home game in the playoffs for baseball's American League Championship series, and a sea of fans wearing blue T-shirts are filling downtown Toronto ahead of the big game.
label: body

text: But will blue be the dominant colour for the other big result of the night? After nearly a decade in power, the Conservatives (the blue team in this political race) are fighting to stay in office.
label: body

text: The Liberals (red) led by the photogenic Justin Trudeau have been ahead in the polls. If they win it'll be a stunning victory for a party which began this race in third.
label: body

text: If Mr Harper hangs on, he'll pull off an equally impressive feat in becoming the first prime minister to win a fourth term in more than a century. Either way this election will be historic. Will Canadians plump for continuity or change?
label: body

text: Speaking in Calgary, Alberta, on Sunday, Mr Trudeau urged voters to "come together as a country".
label: body

text: Mr Trudeau's father, Pierre, is considered the father of modern Canada.
label: body

text: Tom Mulcair, with wife Catherine, addressed supporters in Montreal on Sunday
label: nolabel

text: In five words: How you feel about Canada
label: nolabel

text: NDP leader Tom Mulcair, 60, is hoping to build on his party's second-place finish in the 2011 elections.
label: body

text: However, support for the NDP appeared to have fallen in recent weeks.
label: body

text: At a stop in Toronto, Mr Mulcair hit out at the Liberal leader, saying: "They may try to fool you by giving the old car a fresh coat of paint. But as we've seen, the Liberal Party is just as rusted-out underneath as it was when Canadians kicked them out of office for corruption the last time."
label: body

text: Police ‚Äúdisappeared‚Äù more than 7,000 people at an off-the-books interrogation warehouse in Chicago, nearly twice as many detentions as
label: body

text: Homan Square: an interactive portrait of detainees at Chicago's police facility
font-family: 'Guardian Egyptian Web', 'Guardian Text Egyptian Web', Georgia, serif
label: nolabel

font-family: 'Guardian Egyptian Web', 'Guardian Text Egyptian Web', Georgia, serif
label: nolabel

text: From August 2004 to June 2015, nearly 6,000 of those held at the facility were black, which represents more than twice the proportion of the city‚Äôs population. But only 68 of those held were allowed access to attorneys or a public notice of their whereabouts, internal police records show.
label: body

text: The new disclosures, the result of an ongoing Guardian transparency lawsuit and investigation, provide the most detailed, full-scale portrait yet of the truth about
label: body

text: , a secretive facility that Chicago police have described as little more than a low-level narcotics crime outpost where the mayor has said police ‚Äúfollow all the rules‚Äù.
label: body

text: The police portrayals contrast sharply with those of Homan Square detainees and their lawyers, who insist that ‚Äúif this could happen to someone, it could happen to anyone‚Äù. A 30-year-old man named Jose, for example, was one of the few detainees with an attorney present when he surrendered to police. He said officers at the warehouse questioned him even after his lawyer specifically told them he would not speak.
label: body

text: ‚ÄúThe Fillmore and Homan boys,‚Äù Jose said, referring to police and the facility‚Äôs cross streets, ‚Äúdon‚Äôt play by the rules.‚Äù
label: body

text: According to an analysis of data disclosed to the Guardian in late September, police allowed lawyers access to Homan Square for only 0.94% of the 7,185 arrests logged over nearly 11 years. That percentage aligns with
label: body

text: police‚Äôs broader practice of providing minimal access to attorneys during the crucial early interrogation stage, when an arrestee‚Äôs constitutional rights against self-incrimination are most vulnerable.
label: body

text: But Homan Square is unlike Chicago police precinct houses, according to lawyers who described a ‚Äúfind-your-client game‚Äù and experts who reviewed data from the latest tranche of arrestee records obtained by the Guardian.
label: body

text: That place was and is scary. There's nothing about it that resembles a police station
font-family: 'Guardian Egyptian Web', 'Guardian Text Egyptian Web', Georgia, serif
label: nolabel

text: ‚ÄúNot much shakes me in this business ‚Äì baby murder, sex assault, I‚Äôve done it all,‚Äù said David Gaeger, an attorney whose client was taken to Homan Square in 2011 after being arrested for marijuana. ‚ÄúThat place was and is scary. It‚Äôs a scary place. There‚Äôs nothing about it that resembles a police station. It comes from a Bond movie or something.‚Äù
label: body

text: The narcotics, vice and anti-gang units operating out of Homan Square, on Chicago‚Äôs west side, take arrestees to the nondescript warehouse from all over the city: police data obtained by the Guardian and mapped against the city grid show that 53% of disclosed arrestees come from more than 2.5 miles away from the warehouse. No contemporaneous public record of someone‚Äôs presence at Homan Square is known to exist.
label: body

text: Nor are any booking records generated at Homan Square, as confirmed by a sworn deposition of a police researcher in late September, further preventing relatives or attorneys from finding someone taken there.
label: body

text: ‚ÄúThe reality is, no one knows where that person is at Homan Square,‚Äù said Craig Futterman, a professor at the University of Chicago Law School who studies policing. ‚ÄúThey‚Äôre disappeared at that point.‚Äù
label: body

text: A Chicago police spokesman did not respond to a list of questions for this article, including why the department had doubled its initial arrest disclosures without an explanation for the lag. ‚ÄúIf lawyers have a client detained at Homan Square, just like any other facility, they are allowed to speak to and visit them,‚Äù the police claimed in
label: body

font-family: 'Guardian Egyptian Web', 'Guardian Text Egyptian Web', Georgia, serif
label: body

text: Twenty-two people have told the Guardian that Chicago police kept them at Homan Square for hours and even days. They describe pressure from officers to become informants, and all but two ‚Äì both white ‚Äì have said the police denied them phone calls to alert relatives or attorneys of their whereabouts.
label: body

text: Their accounts point to violations of
label: body

text: , which say police must ‚Äúcomplete the booking process‚Äù regardless of their interest in interrogating a suspect and must also ‚Äúallow the arrestee to make a reasonable number of telephone calls to an attorney, family member or friend‚Äù, usually within ‚Äúthe first hour‚Äù of detention.
label: body

text: The most recent disclosure of Homan Square data provides the scale behind those accounts: the demographic trends within the 7,185 disclosed arrests at the warehouse are now far more vast
label: body

text: than what the Guardian reported in August after launching the transparency lawsuit
label: body

text: ‚Äì but are consistently disproportionate in terms of race and constitutional access to legal counsel.
label: body

text: 82.2% of people detained at Homan Square were black, compared with 32.9% of the Chicago population.
label: body

text: 11.8% of detainees in the Homan Square logs were Hispanic, compared with 28.9% of the population.
label: body

text: 5.5% of the detainees were white, compared with 31.7% of the population.
label: body

text: Of the 68 people who Chicago police claim had access to counsel at Homan Square, however, 45% were black, 26% were Hispanic and another 26% were white.
label: body

text: ‚ÄúOperating a massive, red-brick warehouse between two of the most crime-filled areas in the city of Chicago, equipped with floodlights, cameras, razor-wire ‚Äì this near-paramilitary wing of the government that we‚Äôve created, I would say that people who live close to it know what purpose it serves the most,‚Äù said the attorney Gaeger. ‚ÄúThe demographics that surround it speak for themselves.‚Äù
label: body

text: Despite the lack of booking and minimal attorney access at Homan Square, it is not a facility for detaining and interrogating the most violent of Chicago‚Äôs criminals. Drug possession charges were eventually levied in 5,386 of the disclosed Homan Square arrests, or 74.9%; heroin accounted for 35.4% of those, with marijuana next at 22.3%.
label: body

text: The facility‚Äôs use by police has intensified in recent years. Nearly 65% of documented Homan Square arrests since August 2004 took place in the five years since Rahm Emanuel, formerly Barack Obama‚Äôs top aide, became mayor. (The Guardian has filed a Foia request with Emanuel‚Äôs office to disclose the extent of its involvement in Homan Square.)
label: body

text: The 68 documented attorney visits are actually slightly higher, statistically speaking, than the extremely minimal legal access Chicago police provide suspects in custody during the initial stages of their arrest. The 2014 citywide total at declared police stations, according to First Defense Legal Aid,
label: body

text: . On face value, the lawyer visit rate at Homan Square, according to the newly disclosed documents, was 0.9% over nearly 11 years.
label: body

text: But those documents do not tell the entire story of Homan Square. Chicago police have not disclosed any figures at all on people who were detained at Homan Square but never ultimately charged. Nor has it released any information about detentions or arrests before September 2004, claiming that information is burdensome to produce because it is not digital. (Chicago purchased the warehouse in 1995.)
label: body

text: ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs hard to believe that 7,185 arrests is an accurate number of arrestees at Homan Square,‚Äù said the University of Chicago‚Äôs Futterman. ‚ÄúEven if it were true that less than 1% of Homan arrestees were given access to counsel, that would be abhorrent in and of itself.‚Äù
label: body

text: ‚ÄòTry finding a phone number for Homan‚Äô
font-family: 'Guardian Egyptian Web', 'Guardian Text Egyptian Web', Georgia, serif
label: body

text: Arrestees often are not processed at the Homan Square facility, in apparent violation of Chicago police directives. Photograph: The Guardian
font-family: 'Guardian Text Sans Web', 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, 'Lucida Grande', sans-serif
label: nolabel

text: Chicago attorneys say they are not routinely turned away from police precinct houses, as they are at Homan Square. The warehouse is also unique in not generating public records of someone‚Äôs detention there, permitting police to effectively hide detainees from their attorneys.
label: body

text: ‚ÄúTry finding a phone number for Homan to see if anyone‚Äôs there. You can‚Äôt, ever,‚Äù said Gaeger. ‚ÄúIf you‚Äôre laboring under the assumption that your client‚Äôs at Homan, there really isn‚Äôt much you can do as a lawyer. You‚Äôre shut out. It‚Äôs guarded like a military installation.‚Äù
label: body

text: The difficulty lawyers have in finding phone numbers for Homan Square mirrors the difficulties that arrestees at the warehouse have in making phone calls to the outside world. Futterman called the lack of phone access at Homan Square a critical problem.
label: body

label: body

label: body

text: Lawyer Rajeev Bajaj was allowed into Homan Square to see one of his clients in 2006. text: Jose wasn‚Äôt home. But his wife and 10-year-old daughter were, as well as his daughter‚Äôs friend, who had come over to work on a school project.

text: East Jerusalem Becomes Focus Of The Conflict, And The Mood Is Bleak
label: title

text: Israeli police check Palestinian IDs at a checkpoint in an Arab neighborhood of Jerusalem on Sunday. Palestinian assailants have carried out a series of stabbings and the Israelis have ramped up security measures in the city. Eight Israelis and more than 30 Palestinians have been killed in recent violence.
label: nolabel

text: Palestinians sit in a line of idling cars that stretches downhill, waiting to be allowed out of their East Jerusalem neighborhood via a road partially sealed off by Israeli police.
label: body

text: Around the corner, Palestinian driver Waleed Mattar has stopped the school bus at a row of new, sharp-edged concrete cubes blocking his usual route. The kids now have a long walk home.
label: body

text: This is a neighborhood in East Jerusalem called Jabel Mukaber, with a population of more than 20,000 and a median age of just 18.
label: body

text: Israel has stepped up its already tight security, and shop owner Adel Aweisat says new measures, including a 20-foot-high barrier between this place and a nearby Jewish neighborhood, are ratcheting up pressure here.
label: body

text: Israel's security Cabinet said it erected blocks and barriers because of safety concerns. In a recent meeting, the Cabinet said some Palestinian neighborhoods in East Jerusalem are "centers of friction and incitement."
label: body

text: In the Israeli-Palestinian fighting that dates back decades, East Jerusalem has rarely been the center of the violence. Yet eight Israelis have been killed in attacks this month, and Israeli authorities say several perpetrators were young Palestinians from East Jerusalem armed with knives. More than 40 Palestinians have been killed. Some were killed in clashes with Israel's security forces, while others were attackers or would-be attackers, police say.
label: body

text: Israel captured East Jerusalem from Jordan in the 1967 Mideast war and claims the entire city as its capital. The Palestinians, in turn, are demanding the eastern part of the city as the capital of a future Palestinian state.
label: body

text: Kerry On Holy Site In Jerusalem: 'We're Not Seeking Outsiders Or Others To Come In'
label: nolabel

text: In most of Israel and the West Bank, Jews and Arabs live largely segregated lives. There is still a fair degree of mixing in Jerusalem, but the recent violence is keeping the two sides apart.
label: body

text: With Violent Clashes On The Rise, Israel Builds Wall In East Jerusalem
label: nolabel

text: We have to leave our car at the concrete blocks so we hitch a ride with Ahmed Aweisat. He's 21 and studying to be a dentist. Plenty of Palestinians in Jerusalem have qualifications, and some have decent jobs. But still, he says, being a Palestinian in Jerusalem is hard.
label: body

text: He points out a wall cutting off another Arab area, a checkpoint, a watchtower and a road only Israeli security forces are allowed to drive along. He doesn't endorse attacks on Israelis, but says they stem from frustrations all Palestinians feel.
label: body

text: When we visit another branch of the Aweisat family, they are receiving condolences.
label: body

text: Two of their boys recently were shot dead by police. Baha was 23, and Moataz was 16. Police say Baha was involved in a fatal attack against Jewish Israeli civilians on a bus and that Moataz tried to stab an Israeli police officer on another occasion. The family claims the younger boy would never have done that, though they don't deny the charge against his older cousin.
label: body

text: When I speak with Baha's father, Mohammad, he tells me he himself was convicted in 1975 of a bombing that killed 15 civilians.
label: body

text: He expresses no regret for his actions or for those of his son, but he says he's surprised nothing's changed in 40 years ‚Äî he had hoped his children would have a different life.
label: body

text: Meanwhile, many Palestinian youths say their elders have failed them. In a caf√© near the Hebrew University, I meet Budour Hassan, a Palestinian who is a master's student and a blogger.
label: body

text: "They are totally disillusioned," she says of the young Palestinians.
label: body

text: Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has criticized Palestinian leaders, saying they are inciting violence. However, Hassan says young people aren't listening to Palestinian politicians.
label: body

text: "They are not waiting for anyone because they know that no one's coming. They are not waiting for Arab leaders; they are not waiting for Palestinian leaders," she says.
label: body

text: She sees those Arab and Palestinian leaders as failures. Some tried diplomacy, others tried violence, but she says none improved the lives of Palestinians. Hassan doesn't condone the recent attacks but says many young people here no longer see any peaceful, or political, way forward.
label: body

text: House Conservatives Brace for GOP Blowback in Leadership Fight
label: title

text: Establishment Republicans could soon use the conservatives' own tactics against them
label: body

text: drove Speaker John Boehner to quit
label: body

text: forced his most likely successor out of the race
label: body

text: ‚Äîhas a nightmare scenario on its hands. It isn‚Äôt that Boehner stays on as Speaker, or that
label: body

text: or even would-be Speaker Kevin McCarthy ends up replacing him. It‚Äôs that establishment Republicans could soon use the conservatives‚Äô own tactics against them.
label: body

text: The caucus of about three-dozen members has caused chaos on Capitol Hill in recent weeks, forcing Boehner‚Äôs retirement and bringing down the candidacy of his heir, House Majority Leader McCarthy. But as every one in Washington holds their breath to see if Ryan tries to pursue the job he‚Äôs told everyone he doesn‚Äôt want‚Äîand with some conservatives like Sen. Ted Cruz
label: body

text: questioning if Ryan is even one of them
label: body

text: ‚Äîit‚Äôs worth noting what the other wing of the Republican Party is up to.
label: body

text: Don‚Äôt call them ‚Äúmoderates,‚Äù because in any other caucus they‚Äôd be conservative. So let‚Äôs call the 56-member coalition known as the Tuesday Group ‚Äúpragmatists‚Äù‚Äîor, for lack of a better word, the establishment. Just about the only thing that the establishment and the Freedom Caucus agree upon is that something‚Äôs got to change. ‚ÄúWhoever is the next Speaker, if he or she chooses path of appeasement of rejectionist wing of the party, we‚Äôll be stuck on path of paralysis and speaker will be ineffective,‚Äù says Rep. Charlie Dent, a Pennsylvania Republican who chairs the Tuesday Group. ‚ÄúWe have to change the underlying governing dynamic going forward.‚Äù
label: body

text: To make his point, Dent and his colleagues
label: body

text: signed on to a bipartisan petition
label: body

text: earlier this month to reauthorize the obscure Export-Import Bank over the objections of the Freedom Caucus. Dent notes that any real governing‚Äîthe passage of Senate-brokered compromises usually opposed by the conservative insurgents‚Äîwill have to go through his group working with Democrats. ‚Äú[Ryan] understands the circumstances he faces,‚Äù Dent says. ‚ÄúHe clearly understands that he‚Äôs going to have to move some important legislation as speaker‚Äîthe debt ceiling, an omnibus‚Äîand if does those things he‚Äôll be sniped out from his right flank.‚Äù
label: body

text: This is the same box that Boehner and McCarthy faced and punted on: whether to turn the conference to the left to avoid catastrophes for the Republican Party like shutting down the government or defaulting on the nation‚Äôs debt, or stick to a right-wing course at a time when outsiders like Donald Trump, Ben Carson and Carly Fiorina are dominating the presidential election.
label: body

text: ‚ÄúConservatives are simply asking leadership to make good on their campaign promises, but it‚Äôs moderates who are joining with liberal Democrats to resurrect the cronyist Export-Import Bank that subsidizes privileged corporations,‚Äù says former South Carolina Sen. Jim DeMint, who now heads The Heritage Foundation. ‚ÄúThe current majorities were elected on promises to stop amnesty and fight for full repeal of Obamacare, and the next Speaker needs to lay out an agenda that ends favoritism toward special interests and provides opportunity to all Americans.‚Äù
label: body

text: The problem is, the leaders were never going to make good on their campaign promises: They don‚Äôt control the White House or a big enough majority in the Senate to deliver. So, in frustration, the Freedom Caucus has gone after the system itself, particularly its leaders. ‚ÄúDisorder and chaos are not the traditional conservative vales,‚Äù scoffs Dent. ‚ÄúThe rejectionist arm of the party seems to have a problem with James Madison and the system [of checks and balances] that he devised.‚Äù
label: body

text: Dent essentially argues that two can play the game of disruption the Freedom Caucus has devised. If it only takes 30 votes for a Republican to lose a floor vote for Speaker (the GOP majority of 247 minus 30 is 217, below the 218 needed to pass a motion), those votes can be found elsewhere if need be. ‚ÄúIf there are somewhere between 30 and 50 Republican members who say they won‚Äôt vote for the choice of the majority of Republicans for speaker, well then yes, the Democrats will have an impact and influence on who will be the next speaker if there aren‚Äôt 217 votes on the House floor,‚Äù Dent says. ‚ÄúI would prefer we elect a Speaker on majority-Republican votes on the House floor. I‚Äôm just not sure that‚Äôs possible.‚Äù
label: body

text: But the Freedom Caucus has bigger worries than competing voting blocs: The establishment is taking another page from its playbook by going after them in primaries. One of the demands of the Freedom Caucus is that the leadership and allied groups not run ads against them when they buck the system. ‚ÄúWe‚Äôre asking for assurances that the next Speaker or any of his allies, including the Chamber of Commerce and the American Action Network, will not run ads against us as has happened over
label: body

text: to many of us,‚Äù says Rep. David Brat, who defeated former House Majority Leader Eric Cantor in his Virginia primary last year.
label: body

text: Many have asked for support from the National Congressional Campaign Committee, which works to elect Republicans to the House. But given that Freedom Caucus districts lean strongly Republican, there‚Äôs little chance that those members will receive NRCC funds, which tend to go to more competitive swing districts.
label: body

text: Whoever becomes the next Speaker has his or her work cut out for them in managing a party engaged in a low-grade civil war. On the legislative, procedural and electoral fronts, the two wings of the party are vying for dominance. And to lead one is, by definition, to be against the other.
label: body

text: Exactly 30 years ‚Äî and 42 million consoles sold ‚Äî after its debut on American shores, it seems like the Nintendo Entertainment System was destined to be a success.
label: body

text: But in the early 1980s, things were quite a bit dicier. Nintendo was worried about the viability of home consoles; it wasn't sure how to escape the fate of other U.S. game-makers, who were crippled when market saturation led to a crash in 1983, which in turn left very little demand for home gaming consoles. (Things got so bad that thousands of game cartridges were sent be
label: body

text: buried in a New Mexico landfill
label: body

text: In 1985, the shadow of Atari's failure in the U.S. loomed even across the Pacific Ocean.
label: body

text: 30 years ago, 'Mario' changed the game ‚Äî for good
label: nolabel

text: The NES had been released in Japan two years earlier as the Famicom, a condensing of "Family Computer." On that side of the world, it wasn't a success out of the gate, selling just 440,000 consoles. Even so, the man in charge of creating the console's original hardware ‚Äî Masayuki Uemura ‚Äî tells Mashable that Nintendo's then-President Hiroshi Yamauchi believed that the company could sell at least a million consoles in the U.S. market.
label: body

text: Masayuki Uemura, lead architect of the Nintendo Entertainment System hardware.
label: nolabel

text: "Our thoughts at the time were that the video game medium was something that had been born originally in America," Uemura told
label: body

text: during a visit to New York to celebrate the NES's 30th anniversary. "Although we had made the Famicom, we were thinking it might not be well-suited to Japan."
label: body

text: So Nintendo's American office, already established thanks to the company's strong arcade game business, began researching the likelihood of bringing the Famicom to the States. That's when Nintendo's distributors, already burned by Atari's collapse and bankruptcy that unpurchased stock on the shelves, tried to frantically warn the company off.
label: body

text: Uemura recalled seeing advertisements at CES for the ColecoVision and the Commodore 64 console. Both included a keyboard, a precedent set by Atari when it insisted its consoles were "computer systems, and not toys."
label: body

text: It was the opinion at the time that the age of video game consoles in America had passed
label: nolabel

text: It was the opinion at the time that the age of video game consoles in America had passed
label: body

text: and it had moved on to personal computing at home, and people using personal computers," Uemura explained.
label: body

text: Arcade cabinets, show us the way
label: body

text: Nintendo's arcade business was doing well in America, as restaurants and bars added arcade cabinets that featured plenty of Nintendo games. Aside from the wildly popular
label: body

text: , Nintendo's cabinets were unique in that some featured two screens that allowed a pair of players to compete head to head.
label: body

text: But what most people don't know, according to Uemura, is that this was actually the Famicom's secret debut in the United States. Two of those tiny game consoles were used to power the two-player arcade experience. Players could compete in Nintendo's
label: body

text: , each controlling a player on a separate screen. To help generate more revenue, Nintendo of America even set up the cabinets so each side could play a separate game, including
label: body

text: An advertisement for Nintendo's arcade cabinets, known as the Vs. System
label: nolabel

text: These arcade cabinets became so popular that an early 1980s gaming publication called
label: body

text: ranked them as some of the most popular in the country. That's when Uemura said that Nintendo began to reconsider bringing the Famicom to America.
label: body

text: "We discovered the distributors that stood in between the game creators, which were us, and the players were an unnecessary piece. While some of the distributors weren't as big of a fan of these larger arcade cabinets, the users really liked what we were putting out, and we had that link to the player base," he said.
label: body

text: "This lead us to conclude, as we had seen with the arcade distributors, [that] if we were going to move into this space, we could appeal directly to the player and say, 'Hey, we have a system we think you'll like.' We had seen we could attract players directly and skip past the distributor step."
label: body

text: The Nintendo Entertainment System next to the Famicom
label: nolabel

text: At the time, Uemura said, it was vital for Nintendo not to get mixed up in the bitter taste that Atari had left in American's mouths.
label: body

text: While that company had produced successful games, its image was tarnished by a gold rush of cheap products that were designed and programmed in just a few weeks. The most memorable example,
label: body

text: , was produced so quickly that the game itself was barely functional; thousands of
label: body

text: "For our strategy, one of the things we thought was most important was to overcome this image that home gaming wasn't popular, which had unfortunately happened due to Atari's system," Uemura explained. "But we also realized [that]
label: body

text: the moment people saw what we were bringing out and thought 'oh, this is just another Atari,' we would lose them.
label: body

text: the moment people saw what we were bringing out and thought 'oh, this is just another Atari,' we would lose them.
label: body

text: So Nintendo's team went to work, using three strategies to differentiate the Famicom's American form from anything that remotely resembled an Atari game console.
label: body

text: The VCR had gained popularity in the early 1980s. Nintendo thought it could position the NES in a similar way: as companion technology to the television.
label: body

text: "That's one of the reasons you saw the front-loading in the NES originally ‚Äî because that's how you put video tapes into a VCR. It was similar thing," Uemura said. It's also something Atari didn't do; consoles produced by Nintendo's rival were top-loading, just like the Japanese Famicom. (There were also concerns that in parts of the U.S. with dry climates, static electricity from the user's hand could short-circuit the NES when they were inserting and removing games.)
label: body

text: The Atari factor was also why, despite much deliberation, Nintendo decided to keep the plus-shaped directional pad on its controllers when it brought them to the U.S. That button formation is now ubiquitous for gamers.
label: body

text: The Famicom player 1 controller, with its plus-sign directional pad.
label: nolabel

text: "Atari was famous for their joystick," Uemura said. "We were a little worried if it would be a success or not, but we knew it was different from Atari ‚Äî and we knew when people saw it they could see that difference immediately."
label: body

text: Formatting the controller like this wasn't just a way to look different. Games like
label: body

text: generally scrolled left and right, so the directional pad made sense ‚Äî and as Uemura said, the game's precision jumps just couldn't be made on a joystick.
label: body

text: Finally, the name itself could help Nintendo define itself ‚Äî while also learning from Atari's own strategy. Instead of going by "Family Computer" in the U.S., Nintendo elected to move in a different direction. It did, however, end its console's name with "system" ‚Äî because that's what Atari had done.
label: body

text: "We decided to put Entertainment in the middle. We thought we could maybe piggyback a little bit [on] the naming idea Atari had had, but put something with a little more dynamism and attraction in the middle," Uemura explained. "So that's how it became the NES."
label: body

text: It's been three decades since the Nintendo Entertainment System launched in New York, on Oct. 18, 1985. Uemura is shocked to see that three decades later, fans' passion for the console is stronger than ever. "I was so surprised to find that in Japan and, America as well, that over these 30 years, the interest in the history hasn't disappeared," he said.
label: body

text: He also spoke about his son and daughter, who were about 10 at the time of the Famicom's release and helped him debug games at home before it launched.
label: body

text: "This was something they cherish about being kids at that time, was going to school and that was everyone was talking about the Famicom," he said. "When they get together now, in their alumni groups or whatever, these are people who are 40 ‚Äî the topics that are sure to come up are the Famicom and 'those times.'
label: body

text: "The fact the Famicom succeeded after the game market fell apart with the shock from Atari could be said by some to be a miracle," he concluded. "But this was something that we believed in and we created because we thought it would be a success. We went with that belief ‚Äî and it stands as a testament that 30 years later, it's still being talked about. And I'm proud of that."
label: body

text: When the invasion of Iraq triggered an insurgency, a civil war, and the collapse of social order, Colin Powell coined the ‚ÄúPottery Barn rule‚Äù about military intervention: ‚ÄúYou break it, you own it.‚Äù In the wake of President Obama‚Äôs Oct. 15 announcement that 5,500 U.S. troops will stay in Afghanistan through the end of his term, I hereby proclaim the ‚ÄúHotel California rule,‚Äù after the last line of the Eagles song: ‚ÄúYou can check out anytime you like, but you can never leave.‚Äù

text: Obama‚Äôs decision‚Äîa reversal of an earlier plan to pull out entirely from Afghanistan by the end of his presidency‚Äîwas made well before the Taliban‚Äôs assault on the northern town of Kunduz, which raised doubts about the Afghan army‚Äôs ability to defend the country by itself.
label: body

text: Senior administration officials say that, back in March, Obama ordered the Pentagon to conduct a review of how many U.S. troops would be needed to sustain counterterrorism operations in the region. The answer turned out to be 5,500, spread out on three bases (in Kabul, Bagram, and Kandahar), a calculation that Obama endorsed before the Taliban seizure of Kunduz, though that attack (and the Afghan army‚Äôs eventual retaking of the town, with U.S. assistance) sealed the deal.
label: body

text: Three factors shaped the decision. First, in September 2014, one day after he was sworn into office, Afghanistan‚Äôs new president, Mohammad Ashraf Ghani, signed a ‚Äú
label: body

text: ‚Äù permitting U.S. and NATO forces to remain in his country after the international combat mission expired at the end of that year. (Ghani‚Äôs predecessor, Hamid Karzai, had refused to sign the agreement.) On a subsequent trip to Washington in March, Ghani asked Obama to keep the troops there for longer still and promised to form a more inclusive, less corrupt government in Kabul.
label: body

font-family: HelveticaNeue-Light, 'Helvetica Neue Light', 'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif
label: nolabel

text: Second, with Ghani‚Äôs assurances in mind, Obama ordered the Pentagon review on the U.S. military presence, asking those conducting it to look at Afghanistan not so much as this country where we‚Äôd been fighting a war for 13 years but, more, as one of several partners in a global counterterrorism strategy‚Äîin this case, against the Taliban, al-Qaida remnants, and ISIS jihadists who had begun to pop up in the area.
label: body

text: Once any foreign military commitment is made, it doesn‚Äôt take much to get troop levels up to 5,000 or so. An officer in the Pentagon, with experience in special-operations forces, calculates that a couple thousand are needed for counterterrorism operations, a couple thousand to continue training and advising the Afghan army, a thousand to staff a headquarters, and close to a thousand for ‚Äúforce protection‚Äù‚Äîthat is, for armed forces whose job is to defend the other U.S. military personnel.
label: body

text: The third factor, which does hang over the now-almost-14-year-old war in Afghanistan (and which plays a big part in the ‚ÄúHotel California rule‚Äù), is that the American military is not very good at training indigenous armies in countries facing threats from within and without. (See also South Vietnam and Iraq, among others.)
label: body

text: Military training is more complicated than many realize. True, the Taliban, al-Qaida, and ISIS don‚Äôt require advanced training for its recruits, so, it‚Äôs often asked, why should the Afghan or Iraqi army? But the two tasks are different. Insurgents can attack at a time and place of their choosing; if met with force, they can withdraw and attack someplace else. By contrast, armies defending the government have to be strong and ready everywhere, or they need to have the means to move quickly from one place to another.
label: body

text: So training is not just a matter of teaching soldiers how to shoot straight and maneuver on a battlefield (which American trainers do well). If the goal is to turn the fighting completely over to the local armed forces, then training must also involve teaching them how to conduct and call in air strikes, gather intelligence and apply it to tactical operations, move soldiers rapidly from one area to another (which involves flying helicopters or small transport planes), resupply soldiers when they‚Äôre deployed far from the base (logistics), and plan operations on a strategic or theater-wide level.
label: body

text: To do all these things goes well beyond the abilities of American infantry or special-operations forces assigned to a training mission. In other words, the way we currently train, it may never be possible to make our client-armies completely self-reliant.
label: body

text: John Nagl, a retired U.S. Army lieutenant colonel, has long called for the creation of a special advisory corps‚Äîunits whose sole task would be to advise, train, and assist foreign military forces. These advisers would come to a war zone not only with combat skills but also with fluency in the local language and culture. They would help the local senior officers set up and operate a headquarters. They would help senior officials do the same in the ministry of defense. And, as Nagl envisions it, they would not only train troops on a base but also embed with small units of these troops on the battlefield.
label: body

text: American advisers with local troops evoked grim memories of Vietnam‚Äîand Nagl was acknowledging explicitly that, in the sorts of unstable countries where these advisers were likely to be deployed, they would have to stay embedded and advising for a long, long time.
label: body

text: Few American politicians, officers, or ordinary citizens have any appetite for embedding the current teams of American advisers alongside Afghan troops (or Iraqi troops or Syrian rebels) in combat, and for very good reason. label: body

text: Then again, there are other reasons for the failure of training, and they have little to do with the lack of a specialized American advisory corps. In several of the insurgency wars we‚Äôve joined in the past several decades, the local elites‚Äîwho sign on to be our allies‚Äîare corrupt or incompetent at running their countries. The local soldiers feel little loyalty to their commanders or their leaders, while the insurgent rebels are very energized by their cause. No matter how well Americans‚Äîor any outsiders‚Äîmight train and advise such soldiers, they are unlikely to win because they have no desire to risk dying while fighting.
label: body

text: This was certainly the case when Iraqi soldiers‚Äîtrained by America‚Äôs finest at a cost of billions‚Äîfled after the first gunshot when attacked by ISIS marauders in Mosul. Back in late 2009, when President Obama sent more troops to fight in Afghanistan, the senior U.S. officers‚Äîincluding Adm. Mike Mullen, then the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Gen. David Petraeus, who was commander at the time‚Äîtestified that, if the corruption persisted, the Taliban would win, no matter how many American troops joined the fight. The same is true now.

text: I trained soldiers in Iraq and Afghanistan.¬† The corruption is so pervasive, especially in Afghanistan, that front-line troops rarely had enough pay, fuel, ammunition, or even food by the time everyone up the logistics chain took their "cut". ¬†

text: For all these reasons, President Obama has been leery of military adventures. He sent more troops to Afghanistan, giving his commanders a chance to try out a new war strategy; when it didn‚Äôt work as quickly as they said it would, he withdrew the troops and ended the combat mission. He has decided to keep 5,500 trainers, advisers, and counterterrorism forces in Afghanistan for longer than he‚Äôd originally expected because the new Afghan president wants them there, signed a treaty to keep them there, and committed to run an inclusive government‚Äîand because the Afghan army isn‚Äôt ready to go it alone.

text: The premise is to leave it up to the next American president to decide whether the commitment is still worth the effort. text: found that guns were used far more frequently to intentionally scare others ‚Äî loved ones in particular ‚Äî than in legitimate self-defense.
label: body

text: Guns are frightening things. So if you do have a gun, please keep it locked up, and don't bring it to Starbucks. And for gods sake, don't take it out and brandish it. I don't care if
label: body

text: know you're a "good guy with a gun" because I don't know you. You're just a guy with a gun. In a public space. And that really scares the hell out of people.
label: body

text: If you're Bruce Willis in "Die Hard," however, go right ahead and whip that puppy out and fire it indiscriminately with a full 90-degree spread. Don't even think about where the bullets might fall. Just do it.

label: body

label: body

label: body

label: body

text: found states that implemented "safe storage" laws in the early '90s saw a 23% decrease in firearm deaths of children under 15 in a four-year period.
label: body

text: But if you're Bruce Willis in "Die Hard," you don't need to worry about securing your gun because you don't even need to bring one. One will probably just be lying on the floor. Several, in fact. Most likely near the bodies of various East German (?) flunkies. Just take one. And go bonkers.

text: 6. Anger issues and guns are a deadly cocktail.
label: body

text: An April 2015 CBS News report cited a recent study that found about 1 in 10 people with easy access to guns have a documented history of
label: body

text: anger issues and impulsive behavior. According to researchers, that's a recipe for big trouble
label: body

text: Unless you're a loner, estranged from his wife with nine years on the force, a chip on his shoulder, and nothing left to lose. In which case...
label: body

text: 7. Your gun is much, much more likely to kill you or a member of your family than a home intruder.
label: body

text: conducted by the NIH found that for every time a gun is used legally in self-defense, there are four unintentional shootings, seven assaults or murders, and a whopping 11 suicides or attempted suicides.
label: body

text: If you're Bruce Willis in "Die Hard," however, feel free to ignore these statistics, as your gun only ever kills bad guys ‚Äî 100% of the time.

text: Unfortunately, none of us are Bruce Willis in "Die Hard."
label: body

text: I'm not Bruce Willis in "Die Hard." You're not Bruce Willis in "Die Hard." Nobody is Bruce Willis in "Die Hard." Not even
label: body

text: is Bruce Willis in "Die Hard." He's just Bruce Willis.
