text: This Is How Much Not Having Health Insurance Will Cost Starting in 2016
label: title

text: WASHINGTON (AP) ‚Äî The math is harsh: The federal penalty for having no health insurance is set to jump to $695, and the Obama administration is being urged to highlight that cold fact to help drive its new pitch for health law sign-ups.
label: body

text: That means the 2016 sign-up season starting Nov. 1 could see penalties become a bigger focus to motivate millions of people who have remained eligible for coverage, but uninsured. They‚Äôre said to be more skeptical about the value of health insurance.
label: body

text: Until now, health overhaul supporters have stressed the benefits of getting covered: taxpayer subsidies that pay roughly 70 percent of the monthly premium, financial protection against sudden illness or an accident, and access to regular preventive and follow-up medical care.
label: body

text: But in 2016, the penalty for being uninsured will rise to the greater of either ‚Äì $695 or 2.5 percent of taxable income ‚Äì for someone who goes without coverage for a full 12 months. This year the comparable numbers are $325 or 2 percent of income. While the increase isn‚Äôt good news, it does create a marketing opportunity.
label: body

text: The numbers are pretty clear. With subsidized customers now putting in an average of about $100 a month of their own money, a consumer would be able to get six months or more of coverage for $695, instead of owing that amount to the IRS as a tax penalty. Backers of the law are urging the administration to hammer that home.
label: body

text: ‚ÄúGiven that the penalty is larger, it does make sense to bring it up more frequently,‚Äù said Ron Pollack, executive director of Families USA, a liberal advocacy group. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs an increasing factor in people‚Äôs decisions about whether or not to get enrolled.‚Äù
label: body

text: ‚ÄúMore and more, people are mentioning the sticks as well as the carrots,‚Äù said Katherine Hempstead, director of health insurance coverage for the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation, a nonpartisan organization that has helped facilitate the insurance expansion under Obama‚Äôs law.
label: body

text: Hempstead says the message about penalties resonates with uninsured people, who are generally cash-strapped low- and middle-income workers.
label: body

text: A lot of people cite it as the main reason for signing up, she said. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs the law and they don‚Äôt want to pay the penalty.‚Äù
label: body

text: Administration officials are looking for a balance.
label: body

text: ‚ÄúWe need to be make sure that we are very clear and explicit about that $695 penalty so people understand the choice they are making,‚Äù said spokeswoman Lori Lodes. But she said the main emphasis will stay on the benefits of having health insurance and how the law‚Äôs subsidies can dramatically lower the cost of monthly premiums.
label: body

text: The requirement that individuals get health insurance or face fines remains the most unpopular part of President Barack Obama‚Äôs health care law, a prime target of Republican repeal efforts. It started at $95 or 1 percent of income in 2014. The fact that it‚Äôs up to $695 may take consumers by surprise.
label: body

text: But many experts consider the mandate essential to Obama‚Äôs overall approach, as does the insurance industry. The law forbids insurers from turning away people with health problems, and the coverage requirement forces healthy people into the insurance pool, helping to keep premiums in check. After 2016, the fines will rise with inflation.
label: body

text: This year was the first time the IRS collected the penalties, deducting them from taxpayers‚Äô refunds for the 2014 tax year in most cases. Some 7.5 million households paid penalties totaling $1.5 billion, an average of $200 apiece, according to preliminary IRS data. Separately, another 12 million households claimed exemptions from the mandate because of financial hardships or other reasons.
label: body

text: Although Obama‚Äôs law is five years old and has survived two Supreme Court challenges, administration officials say the upcoming open enrollment season won‚Äôt be easy. It may be a struggle to just keep about the same number of people covered.
label: body

text: The administration has set a goal of 10 million customers enrolled and paying their premiums by the end of 2016 on HealthCare.gov and state insurance markets. That‚Äôs roughly the number covered now, and well below what congressional budget analysts had estimated for 2016. The administration expects most will be returning customers, but 3 million to 4 million will be people who are currently uninsured. There‚Äôs a lot of turnover in the market.
label: body

text: Among the difficulties for next year: Premiums are expected to go up more than they did this year, even if taxpayer subsidies cushion the cost. The most eager customers have already signed up. And many of those remaining appear to be stretching tight household budgets, with other financial priorities, like car repairs or putting money in savings accounts.
label: body

text: Sign-up season starts Nov. 1 and runs through Jan. 31. As a result of the law, the share of people in the United States lacking health insurance is at a historic low of about 9 percent, and the White House wants to keep that trend growing during Obama‚Äôs last full year in office.
label: body

text: China Syndrome Dampens Third Quarter Earnings
label: title

text: China's economic slowdown has left its mark on several third quarter corporate earnings reports.
label: nolabel

text: A woman works in a factory manufacturing solar power panels on Oct. 11, 2015, in central China's Jiangxi province. China's economic growth decelerated in the third quarter but exceeded analysts' expectations.
label: nolabel

text: The bar has been set pretty low for China's economic growth this year ‚Äì so low, in fact, that the country's worst quarter of economic growth since the world was just emerging from the¬†global financial crisis actually surprised analysts to the upside.
label: body

text: Let that sink in for a moment. China on Monday announced its third quarter GDP expanded by only 6.9 percent year over year. The country's titanic economy hadn't previously slowed that much since 2009, immediately following¬†one of the worst international financial crises in decades.
label: body

text: And some analysts actually speculated whether Monday's figures were too good to be true.
label: body

text: "We don't have total confidence in the numbers, and we are surprised by the acceleration in services output given the collapse in the equity market,"
label: body

text: Tom Orlik and Fielding Chen wrote in a research note this week.
label: body

text: Global economists were generally expecting the Chinese economy to have grown about 6.8 percent in July, August and September from a year before ‚Äì dragged down by the country's recent trade slowdown, stock market volatility and currency devaluations that have taken a toll on consumer demand.
label: body

text: "[The Chinese economy] is slowing down, and we have it slowing down further next year. But gosh, 7 percent growth is pretty strong, and so is 6.5 percent next year that we have," Kurt Karl, chief economist at Swiss Re, said in an interview with CNBC's "
label: body

text: ." "The real challenge for the global economy with the transition that China's in now is not so much the slowdown as the shift from investment-led to consumption-led."
label: body

text: But it's hard for multinational firms to appeal to Chinese consumers when
label: body

text: that began in August have made imports more expensive for locals. Imports into China in September plummeted
label: body

text: year over year following August's 5.5 percent drop.
label: body

text: And as third quarter financial data start to roll in, it's clear that international corporations are feeling the sting of higher prices for the goods they sell¬†in China. Nestle S.A. saw sales fall 2 percent in the third quarter and attributed at least some of its weakness to "
label: body

text: ." Yum! Brands, whose operations include Kentucky Fried Chicken, Pizza Hut and Taco Bell, last week announced that¬†operating profit for its China business¬†is expected to be "about flat to prior year, excluding the impact of foreign exchange," which is likely to further drag on the company's finances.
label: body

text: from luxury goods producer Burberry said the company's global sales in the last six months were "impacted by [an] increasingly challenging environment for luxury, particularly Chinese customers." In a conference call, chief financial officer Carol Fairweather said sales in China accounts for "something between 30 percent and 40 percent" of the company's total revenue.
label: body

text: "Retail revenues slowed in the second quarter, reflecting a more challenging external environment for luxury customers ‚Äì with increased global and Chinese stock market volatility, currency swings and concerns over slowing economic growth," Fairweather said in a conference call last week. "We believe this affected the confidence of, and thus demand from, luxury consumers and especially the Chinese customer in some of our key markets."
label: body

text: It's important to keep in mind, however, that most American firms don't actually have much direct exposure to China. Burt White, chief investment officer for LPL Financial, estimates China only accounts for "less than 5 percent of S&P 500 profits," though he notes the country's downturn "is responsible for a lot of the weakness in commodity sector earnings."
label: body

text: But the indirect international consequences of a weakened China should not be overlooked. Although China's GDP growth clocked in at a better-than-expected pace last quarter, the price of oil still dipped further Monday to roughly $46 per barrel on fears that China would ease up on its substantial oil consumption.
label: body

text: Persistently low oil prices have slashed the revenues and workforces of major energy companies like Chevron and Halliburton as they struggle to generate profits, and a further price plunge will do little for such firms' corporate earnings.
label: body

text: recently incurred $257 million in charges during the third quarter "primarily as a result of the downturn in the energy market and its corresponding impact on the company's business outlook."
label: body

text: And trading outfits at the likes of Morgan Stanley, Citigroup and Goldman Sachs have recently posted extremely underwhelming equity trading profits, as markets around the world have been hampered by Chinese volatility and reduced Chinese demand for imports. Whether directly or otherwise, it's difficult to look at particularly weak quarterly earnings performance and not find some sort of smudge left by China.
label: body

text: "This quarter's earnings preview could almost be a copy and paste of the second quarter preview: It looks like we will get meager earnings growth, if we get any at all," White wrote in a recent research note, citing "more evidence of slower growth in China" as a complicating factor in the third quarter.

text: Coming Out Like a Porn Star

text: , Jiz Lee emerges from a pastel pink vulva, t-shirt rising seductively, pants sunk to the ankles. It seems to be a metaphor: The genderqueer porn star (who prefers the pronoun "they") emerging from the depths, in porn and in life.
label: body

text: To date, Lee has starred in over 200
label: body

text: and websites, earning respect as a queer porn legend. "Porn is one of the best things I've ever done, but there were so many stigmas I didn't know how to tell my family about it," Lee said in an email. "That's how I began asking others their stories."
label: body

text: Coming Out Like a Porn Star,
label: body

text: which will be released October 20, features over 50 stories from some of the biggest names in porn‚ÄîJoanna Angel, Stoya, Annie Sprinkle, Nina Hartley, Conner Habib, and many more‚Äîall telling the tales of when they came out to their family, friends, and loved ones as porn performers. "While there have been articles on porn performers telling their parents, or being outed at their vanilla job, the mainstream media usually sensationalizes stories that only further stigmatize," said Lee.
label: body

text: What We Talk About When We Talk About Porn
label: nolabel

text: This book, by contrast, seeks to share an honest portrait of porn, with some contributors citing its liberating features and others denouncing it on moral grounds. As Lee writes in the book, "If we are to overcome these cultural roadblocks and gain rights for sex workers, it is precedent that we create a dialogue that stands firmly on the fact that people who chose to perform in porn are no different than anyone else," positive or negative experiences and views included.
label: body

text: I spoke to some of the book's contributors about their coming out experiences, the changing sexual culture, and what they hope the book can achieve.
label: body

text: When did your career get serious enough that you felt you had to "come out" as a porn star?
label: body

text: ], that's when I started coming out. My friends actually all knew going into it, so it wasn't really that much of a come out, but eventually my family would ask questions about my job and that's when I would tell them. My dad was a little patriarchal, my mom was very capitalist about it‚Äîshe was like,
label: body

text: Oh, well, you'd make a lot of money!
label: body

text: I feel like I only consulted with my best friend about it and she said what I feel like a lot of people tend to say which is, "Are you sure? You know this is forever, right?" I said, "I know, I know." But the rest of my friends were kind of just like starstruck or they had this idea that it was super glamorous, like,
label: body

text: Wow, you're doing this thing now!
label: body

text: "Coming out can be a terrifying and alienating experience. I want people to know it's OK to have those hard experiences and that they're not alone." ‚Äî
label: body

text: Who was the most difficult to tell?
label: body

text: My mom. Her initial reaction was pretty cool, but then just recently we had another conversation where I think she was just triggered. We were talking about what I do for my work and my mom already knew but she started interrogating me about it, like, "Why do you need to get tested? What do you do?" It became kind of almost like a class and a race issue like: My mom said, "I'm a Filipino mom, I don't want to hear about this kind of thing," and that was really hard for me. I was just in tears. It got to the point where my mom was like, "Well, why don't you just find a different job?" And I just told her, "This job allows me to write, so... I wanna keep on doing it."
label: body

text: Before [that fight with my mom], I felt that porn was just a job. But after I had that conversation and how deeply and emotionally I was affected, I was just like, wait, no, this is a part of my identity. I really identify and resonate with what I do and when I thought about getting another job at my mom's suggestion, it just didn't really fit.
label: body

text: Why did you want to share your coming out story?
label: body

text: I feel like it's part of my personality, I'm just naturally a very open person. I'm kind of an edger‚ÄîI like to push people past their comfort zone‚Äîand also just because I didn't feel like there was anything wrong with it. I didn't feel like I had to hide anything or that I should be ashamed.
label: body

text: Sometimes coming out can be a terrifying and alienating experience. I just want people to know it's OK to have those hard experiences and that they're not alone. Jiz contacted me‚Äîthey were in the first porn I ever watched, so just from that I was like, "I'm down!" [After reading the book], I hope people will see performers in a more humanized way and I feel like that's important because we're a very pornographic culture. Porn needs to be seen as something that's OK to watch, not so taboo. Because is it really that taboo if everybody's doing it?
label: body

text: VICE: When did your career get serious enough that you felt you had to "come out" as a porn star?
label: body

text: There was a period of my life when I was relying solely on my sex work money to support myself. You meet someone out somewhere, they ask you what you do‚Äîand I was very honest about it when I was asked. I don't think it's anything I should be ashamed of or that anyone should be ashamed of so I try to be a good ambassador in some way, be above board in terms of being honest about it. So that was really the time when I was oddly the most "coming out-y" in my experience.
label: body

text: I've been relatively blessed. All of my friends are very supportive. I did some events fairly recently that people came out for, so I have a strong community of non-sex workers around me who are super cool and super accepting and are proud of the work I do, which is great. Also, it's great to be connected with people like Jiz and the other authors in
label: body

text: . There's a lot of work that needs to be done [to remove stigma] so it's great to see there are a lot of really smart, capable people out there.

text: At what point in knowing someone do you feel like you should tell them you work in porn?
label: body

text: I don't think the sort of calculus I go through in my head is all that different from what I think a lot of people probably go through in terms of how they deal with someone about work status or whether [you're] seeing someone or not right now, and so on. text: Does this person recognize me? How much does this person think that they know of me?

label: title

text: For years, W. got a pass from his party. Questioning him meant questioning our foreign policy. Those days are over
label: nolabel

text: If the Republican presidential primary race were a Thanksgiving dinner, Donald Trump would be the crazy old uncle who drinks too much and says outrageous things that embarrass everyone at the table. Sometimes those things are embarrassing because they‚Äôre brazenly bigoted, or absurdly boastful, or otherwise generally unconnected to reality. But occasionally he says something embarrassing
label: body

text: repeated tweaking of Jeb Bush for Bush‚Äôs preposterous claim
label: body

text: ¬†that his brother ‚Äúkept us safe‚Äù during his presidency falls into the latter category. Trump‚Äôs mockery is of course more than justified. On its face, Jeb‚Äôs claim would be analogous to Exxon boasting about its record of keeping the Alaskan coastline
label: body

text: , or the governor of Texas taking pride¬†in executing
label: body

text: Jeb‚Äôs defense of his brother on this score is patently absurd, but this should not obscure the fact that, in making the claim, Jeb is merely repeating many years of GOP dogma. That George W. Bush kept the nation safe from terrorism, is, bizarrely enough, something that Republicans argued constantly when he was in office. The argument was (
label: body

text: ) that W. shouldn‚Äôt be held responsible for by far the worst terrorist attack in American history, even though his administration was
label: body

text: , because he only had nine months to do something about it, and Al Qaeda was already around at the time he took office, and also Al Gore is fat.
label: body

text: But in all seriousness, the genuinely freakish doublethink Republicans indulge in on this subject requires further explanation. Two factors help explain why it‚Äôs possible and indeed commonplace for people to give Jeb‚Äôs younger brother a kind of historical mulligan in regard to terrorism, to the point where it‚Äôs necessary for Crazy Uncle Donald to remind everyone that the whole 9/11 thing happened well into W‚Äôs presidency.
label: body

text: First, consider the power of what sociologists call ‚Äúframing.‚Äù The cultural frame that the Republican party has so successfully managed to build up since the days of Ronald Reagan is one in which Democrats are weak‚Äîkneed appeasers and semi-pacifists, while the GOP is the party of strong, war-like Daddy figures, who know how to deal with foreign threats with unsentimental ruthlessness.
label: body

text: You would think it would be impossible to assimilate the 9/11 terrorist attacks to this frame, but you would be wrong. Such is the power of this pre-ordained narrative that, when America suffered a catastrophic terrorist attack under a Republican president, this inconvenient fact was, for enormous numbers of people, magically whisked down a kind of collective memory hole.
label: body

text: The power of this frame to distort perception is evident if we consider a counter-factual in which something like the 9/11 attacks happened during the term of any Democratic president. Imagine if 3,000 Americans had been murdered by foreign terrorists nine months into the Obama administration. It‚Äôs almost inconceivable that it would occur to anyone to claim subsequently that Obama had ‚Äúkept us safe,‚Äù because such a claim wouldn‚Äôt be supported by the powerful distortions of a cultural frame that turned the combat-dodging ne‚Äôer do well son of George H.W. Bush into some sort of heroic warrior.
label: body

text: Second, not ascribing any blame to W. for 9/11 was and is another way of treating the events of that terrible day as a kind of inexplicable cataclysm, that was visited upon the nation by irrational and cowardly evildoers, whose motivations were either impossible to understand, or wholly irrelevant, or both.¬†¬† To try to ascribe any responsibility to the Bush administration for letting 9/11 happen could lead to uncomfortable questions of, among other things, whether and to what extent American foreign policy had played a role in creating the conditions that allowed those attacks to happen.
label: body

text: It‚Äôs understandable that, in the immediate aftermath of the attack, almost no one wanted to consider such questions. Fourteen years later, we no longer have any excuse not to do so ‚Äì and that applies especially to GOP presidential candidate Jeb Bush.

label: author

text: ¬†‚Äî Early Friday morning, the Union County Sheriff's department conducted a child support sweep and arrested 15 people for failure to pay child support for arrears totaling $419,890.42, the department announced today.
label: body

text: Members of the Sheriff's Office Investigations Division-Family Violence Unit conducted the sweep in Union, Linden, Rahway, Roselle and Hillside, according to Union County Sheriff Joseph Cryan.
label: body

text: As a result of their investigation, an additional seven people surrendered to the Sheriff's Office for arrears totaling $171,792.98, Cryan said.
label: body

text: 15 people were arrested and another seven surrendered in the Union County Sheriff's Department's child support sweep Friday morning.
label: nolabel

text: Mercer County child support sweep nets 107 arrests
label: nolabel

text: "Time and time again we are seeing parents struggle because someone has shirked their responsibility," Cryan said in a release. "We want to send a message that if you are not paying your obligation for child support, we will pursue you and we will catch you. If this type of enforcement coerces other parents to pay what they owe, it is worth it."
label: body

text: The round-up was led by Family Violence Unit Commander Lt. Jeffery Coon and Unit Supervisor Sgt. Clifford Meros. All the arrests were made without incident.
label: body

text: Those who were arrested were committed to the Union County Jail pending a Superior Court appearance, Cryan said. The people who surrendered were processed and brought for a Superior Court appearance, he said.

text: Tigers' Daniel Norris reveals he has thyroid cancer
label: title

text: Left-hander first saw growth while with Blue Jays, will undergo surgery
label: nolabel

text: Daniel Norris will be put to the test.
label: body

text: The Detroit Tigers‚Äô young left-handed pitcher¬†announced on¬†Instagram and Twitter this¬†afternoon that he was diagnosed with the disease earlier in the season while playing with the Toronto Blue Jays and will undergo surgery to remove a malignant tumor in the off-season.
label: body

text: He acknowledged playing baseball helped him deal with the troubling diagnosis and that a doctor determined he could wait until after the season to have surgery.
label: body

text: "I've been debating for months as to how or even if I should share this with people," he posted on Instagram. "I'm a firm believer in the power of prayer. So now, I'm asking for prayers.‚Äù
label: body

text: Norris, 22, was acquired from Toronto as the centerpiece of a three-prospect deal¬†at the trade deadline. He went 3-2 with a 3.75 ERA in 13 starts -- eight for the Tigers and five for the Blue Jays --¬†this season.
label: body

text: "I was given the option to shut my year down & get it removed immediately," he wrote. "However, seeing another doctor that determined I could wait until the end of the season reassured my gut feeling. Just Keep Playing."
label: body

text: Tigers general manager Al Avila, who was promoted as Dave Dombrowski's replacement days after the trade deadline,¬†said the team knew about Norris‚Äô cancer prior to the July 30 trade for left-handed ace David Price¬†and that Norris is expected to make a full recovery for spring training. The Tigers declined further comment, citing it as a personal matter. Norris found out about the¬†cancerous growth on his thyroid after he was sent to Triple-A Buffalo, Toronto's top affiliate.
label: body

text: ‚ÄúAny time you‚Äôre getting surgery it‚Äôs a concern but they were aware of it,‚Äù Tigers manager Brad¬†Ausmus said. ‚ÄúI found out about it after the trade but I know Dave (Dombrowski) was aware and Al (Avila) was aware at the time of the trade.‚Äù
label: body

text: ‚ÄúBaseball kept me sane," Norris wrote on Instagram. "Regardless of results on the field, I forgot about it when I was between the lines. Afterall, I was just trying to get the heck out of AAA. & I did. I was revived with an opportunity, a blessing from God, with the Tigers back in the Big Leagues.‚Äù
label: body

text: Norris¬†returned from a¬†three-week stint on the disabled list for a¬†left oblique injury in September, allowing one hit or fewer in three of his final four starts of the season¬†and projects as a middle-of-the-rotation pitcher for the Tigers if healthy next season.
label: body

text: "I think¬†Norris has a chance to be a top-flight guy," retiring Tigers pitching coach Jeff Jones told the Free Press earlier today.
label: body

text: Norris, who was not able to be reached for comment today, asked for prayers that he come out of the surgery 100% cancer-free in the post, which ended with his favorite saying.
label: body

text: aired its 40th anniversary episode in February, many hoped it might be the perfect occasion for Eddie Murphy to return to stand-up comedy. They were off about the timing‚Äîbut only by a little. The moment fans had been waiting 28 years for finally came when Murphy did five minutes of material while accepting the Mark Twain Prize for American Humor at the Kennedy Center on Sunday night. His target: Bill Cosby. Though that might be the comedic equivalent of low-hanging fruit these days, Murphy‚Äôs jokes marked a deliberate shift in his own thinking on the subject in recent months.

text: Hackathon Challenges Developers To Make A Difference In Ag
label: title

text: Brian Milne is a freelance writer and former senior reporter/editor for McClatchy Newspapers, advocating sustainable water technologies and precision agriculture.
label: nolabel

text: Precision Ag Tech Helps California Farmers Grow More With Less¬†Water
label: nolabel

text: Drought one year. Flooding the next.
label: body

text: If we‚Äôve learned anything in the agriculture industry in recent years, it‚Äôs that climate change and extreme weather patterns are the new reality¬†‚Äî and all of us have to plan accordingly to help ensure the safety of our food supply. Developers included.
label: body

text: The plan to keep the agricultural industry thriving now includes the tech sector, with more and more technology and software being adopted in the field to help farmers produce more food in the face of today‚Äôs climate and industry challenges.
label: body

text: One such challenge in recent years has been making sense of the avalanche of data precision agriculture technology is churning out via in-field sensors, weather stations, satellites and GPS monitoring and mapping tools.
label: body

text: In an attempt to make some of those data sources more actionable and user-friendly for the ag industry, the
label: body

text: ,‚Äù a hackathon that runs through Oct. 27 and challenges developers to create applications that leverage new publicly available data from the USDA.
label: body

text: The hackathon is being hosted by
label: body

text: , an online community and competition platform comprised of more than 400,000 software developers, and leverages
label: body

text: hosted on Microsoft‚Äôs Azure cloud-computing platform. The event is also sponsored by agtech partners
label: body

text: ‚ÄúWhat I think makes the challenge great is that we are working to bring new minds to the problem of ensuring a resilient food supply,‚Äù said Lucas Joppa, an environmental scientist at Microsoft. ‚ÄúThe technology and developer communities might not have a deep background in agriculture, but we believe that they have important contributions to make through what they do best ‚Äî including data analytics, recommendation and prediction services and visualizations. By bringing together some of the key USDA data sets into one Farm Data Dashboard, we hope to have reduced some of the data discovery pain for our participants and let them move more quickly into building useful applications and services.‚Äù
label: body

text: The USDA is making much of this data, part of its Agricultural Statistical Service (NASS) and Economic Research Service (ERS), available to the public for the first time.
label: body

text: NASS, for example, has opened up access to its¬†
label: body

text: . CropScape provides geospatial data through annual land cover data sets, while VegScape is a vegetative condition database compiled from satellite data.
label: body

text: Those data sets are considered a jumping off point for app developers, who are encouraged to incorporate other relevant data points, which could include sources from other government agencies such as the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA), the National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) or the United States Geological Survey (USGS).
label: body

text: Agriculture is at the crossroads of some of the world‚Äôs most critical challenges.
label: body

text: ‚Äî Dr. Ann Bartuska, USDA Deputy Under Secretary for Research, Education and Economics
label: body

text: ‚ÄúThe President launched the Climate Data Initiative to leverage the government‚Äôs massive amounts of data to develop new and different ways to address system vulnerabilities to climate change, including vulnerabilities of the food supply,‚Äù said Dr. Ann Bartuska, USDA Deputy Under Secretary for Research, Education and Economics. ‚ÄúThrough our partnership with Microsoft, USDA can make the large amounts of agricultural data that we‚Äôve collected over the last 100 years readily available to the private sector and empower developers to turn this data into innovative tools and solutions for our stakeholders. It is a way for us to connect the dots across different sources like we‚Äôve never done before.‚Äù
label: body

text: The challenge, which supports President Obama‚Äôs
label: body

text: , offers $60,000 in prizes for applications that leverage the USDA data to provide actionable insights into the U.S. food system for farmers, agriculture businesses, scientists or consumers. Microsoft is also granting
label: body

text: to aid university researchers and students who take part in the challenge.
label: body

text: Spurring Investments And Innovation In Agriculture
label: nolabel

text: The Next Food Frontier: How AgTech Can Save The World
label: nolabel

text: AgTech Is The New Queen Of Green
label: nolabel

text: Submissions will be taken through October 27. After a short judging period (November 4-17), winners will be announced December 2.
label: body

text: ‚ÄúThe era of climate-driven agriculture has arrived,‚Äù Bartuska added. ‚ÄúAgriculture is at the crossroads of some of the world‚Äôs most critical challenges: climate change, sustainable food production, providing clean and abundant water, renewable energy, and improving human health. Those challenges are immense, especially when you consider that we must meet the food needs of a world population that is expected to top 9 billion people by mid-century. To meet these challenges, we must take advantage of knowledge from all sectors, and encourage new and innovative thinking.‚Äù
label: body

text: Navy deploying advanced underwater search tools used in Malaysian plane search to find El Faro
label: title

text: The U.S. Navy will use some of the same equipment deployed in the search for missing Malaysian Airlines MH370 in hopes of finding the sunken cargo ship
label: body

text: While the search for survivors‚Äîsix of whom
label: body

text: ‚Äîwas called off a week after the ship sank somewhere near Crooked Island in the Bahamas, the search for answers almost three miles underneath the ocean‚Äôs surface continues. Headed by the National Transportation Safety Board, the investigation as to why the disaster occurred in the first place hinges largely on finding the voyage data recorder, or VDR, which is the ship‚Äôs equivalent of an airplane‚Äôs black box.
label: body

text: Six crew members aboard sunken cargo ship have deep New England ties
label: nolabel

text: Crew position on sunken cargo ship El Faro was Dylan Meklin‚Äôs first job out of college
label: nolabel

text: To look for it, the U.S. Navy‚Äôs search and salvage vessel
label: body

text: is setting sail Monday from Norfolk, Virginia, and should be in the search area by mid-week. On board are three of the most advanced underwater search machines in the world, according to Chris Johnson, media relations manager at Naval Sea Systems Command. And while 15,000 feet is a significant depth, all of these tools can operated up to 20,000 feet below sea level.
label: body

text: The first of these three devices the Navy will use once it gets near the search area is something called a hydrophone, an underwater device which gets towed behind the ship as it listens for the black box.
label: body

text: ‚ÄúThe VDR emits a steady signal at a certain frequency that is able to be heard by hydrophone,‚Äù said Johnson. ‚ÄúAssuming that the black box is working, that it didn‚Äôt malfunction and wasn‚Äôt damaged on sinking, we‚Äôll be able to get a better idea and get closer to where the wreckage actually is.‚Äù
label: body

text: That‚Äôs also assuming they don‚Äôt run out of time: The VDR stops emitting a signal when its battery runs out, about 30 days after the sinking.
label: body

text: If the hydrophone doesn‚Äôt pick up any signal, however, all hope is not lost. The Navy also has an underwater sonar in its arsenal, which is operated from the
label: body

text: , connected to the boat by a fiber optic cable.
label: body

text: ‚ÄúWhat that does is maps the ocean floor, looking for signs of wreckage,‚Äù Johnson said. ‚ÄúAnd once we find something we want to take a look at, we send down the remote operated vehicle.‚Äù
label: body

text: The remote operated vehicle is equipped with video and still cameras. It maneuvers around the wreckage, picking things up and bringing them back up to the ship to be examined. Hopefully one such object will be the VDR.
label: body

text: ‚ÄúThen the NTSB can begin piecing together what happened,‚Äù Johnson said. ‚ÄúAnd from there, it's up to the NTSB what they want to do next, if anything.‚Äù
label: body

text: 17-year-old charged with manslaughter in 2014 deaths of 2 high school basketball players
label: title

text: Hannah Elizabeth Reed, 17, has been charged with manslaughter following a 2014 car accident that was a result of her erratic driving, according to Mobile county DA Ashley Rich. (MCSO)
label: nolabel

text: Hannah Elizabeth Reed, 17, has been charged in the death of two south Alabama high school basketball players who died as a result of her erratic driving a year ago, according to Mobile County District Attorney Ashley Rich.
label: body
